Here's a minimal API endpoint handling multipart form uploads with images and a description:

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Http.Features;

var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

// Raise the max request body size to 50 MB
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(o =>
    o.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 50 * 1024 * 1024);

var app = builder.Build();

app.MapPost("/upload", async (HttpRequest request) =>
{
    // Ensure the request is multipart/form-data
    if (!request.HasFormContentType)
        return Results.BadRequest("Expected a multipart/form-data request.");

    var form = await request.ReadFormAsync();

    var description = form["description"].ToString();
    var files = form.Files.GetFiles("images");

    if (files.Count == 0)
        return Results.BadRequest("No image files provided.");

    var saved = new List<string>();

    foreach (var file in files)
    {
        // Validate content type
        if (!file.ContentType.StartsWith("image/"))
            return Results.BadRequest($"'{file.FileName}' is not an image.");

        var safeName = $"{Guid.NewGuid()}{Path.GetExtension(file.FileName)}";
        var path = Path.Combine("uploads", safeName);

        Directory.CreateDirectory("uploads");
        await using var stream = File.Create(path);
        await file.CopyToAsync(stream);

        saved.Add(safeName);
    }

    return Results.Ok(new { description, uploadedFiles = saved });
})
.DisableAntiforgery();   // required for minimal APIs accepting form data

app.Run();
```

**Key points:**

- **`ConfigureKestrel`** — raises the default 30 MB body limit to 50 MB.
- **`ReadFormAsync`** — parses the multipart form; `form.Files.GetFiles("images")` grabs all files under that field name.
- **`.DisableAntiforgery()`** — needed in .NET 8+ minimal APIs for form endpoints (without it you get a 400).
- Content-type check rejects non-image uploads early.

**Test with `curl`:**

```bash
curl -X POST http://localhost:5000/upload \
  -F "description=My vacation photos" \
  -F "images=@photo1.jpg" \
  -F "images=@photo2.png"
```

If you prefer a **strongly-typed** approach instead of raw `HttpRequest`, you can bind with `[FromForm]`:

```csharp
app.MapPost("/upload", async ([FromForm] string description,
                              IFormFileCollection images) =>
{
    // same logic as above
});
```

Both styles work — the explicit `HttpRequest` version gives you more control over validation.
